<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-22T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-22T03:00:00-05:00" n="678" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d678">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 654.119/400</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SPA1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Stovall</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Berne</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-22T09:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 22, 1918, 9 a.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received July 24, 11.03
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>4037. For War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_DEL1">Dresel</persName>]:</p>
                            <p>No. 1001 [<hi rend="italic">101</hi>]. Cotton agreement has finally
                                been ratified by British, French, and Italian delegates and only
                                awaits formal acceptance by Swiss of following modification in order
                                to take full effect. British Government has ratified with
                                reservation that total of exports under heading A, B, C, and E,
                                pages 1 and 2 of agreement, shall not exceed 300 metric tons per
                                annum. Exports for <pb facs="0803" n="1637" xml:id="pg_1637"/>
                                April, May, and June this year were at approximately this rate.
                                Instructions to French delegates provide for acceptance figures for
                                1917.</p>
                            <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SPA1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stovall</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>